[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Earlier this year, online payments changed forever, and you probably didn\'t even notice. Every internet user has heard of the HTTP status code 404 not found. But if you\'re a web developer, you might have nightmares about status code 500, internal server error, which'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'happens when your shoddy deployed code breaks in production. But there\'s one HTTP status code that\'s just been sitting there since 1997, waiting for its moment to shine, 402, payment required. It was reserved for future use'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'back when the web was young and optimistic. But now, three decades later, we\'re still figuring out how to handle money on the internet without giving platforms like Stripe a 3% cut before the privilege of pressing some buttons. Well, that\'s about to change'

[00:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'thanks to a new protocol developed by Coinbase called X42 that enables micro payments that can turn every API request into a tiny cash register with zero fees. And what\'s especially crazy is that these payments are instantaneous,'

[00:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'frictionless, and open the door for machine toachine payments. Like, imagine an entire AI economy where AI agents are paying other AI agents to do whatever AI agents do. What could possibly go wrong? In today\'s video, we\'ll find out by'

[01:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'taking a closer look at X42 and its promise to revolutionize the way money moves on the internet. It is November 26, 2025, and you\'re watching the Code Report. One thing that sucks about platforms like Stripe is that they charge a 30 cent fee per transaction,'

[01:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which makes them overly complex for certain use cases. Like if you have an API where you charge one penny per request you\'d be running at a negative 3,000% profit margin. That\'s not acceptable even by Silicon Valley'

[01:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'standards. So the solution is to force users to authenticate OOTH to verify a credit card, then either buy subscriptions or credits on your platform for a higher dollar amount and then replenish them when they run out. It\'s complicated, but X42 dramatically'

[01:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'simplifies this workflow. In fact, it only takes one line of middleware code in Node.js to get up and running. If a buyer makes a request to a paid API endpoint, the server responds with an HTTP 402 code, which means a payment is'

[01:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'required to complete the request. The user would then see a page like this asking them to connect a wallet at which point the transaction can be completed without subscriptions, authentication, or any other friction. In addition, the'

[02:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'process can be done programmatically on the buyer side using handwritten code or even AI agents. Pretty cool. But now, let\'s actually deploy our own monetized API from scratch. Before doing that though, we need a reliable back-end'

